metadata.name: barcode(fxhash) #354
metadata.description:
[UPDATED: There was a bug in the first edition of this token that has been solved in this. All minters of the previous edition, has a reserve of 2]

barcode(fxhash) converts the ascii characters from the transaction hash of the token (fxhash variable) into barcodes for each of 51 characters. It uses Code 39 (https://github.com/graphicore/librebarcode), so it is not case sensitive. Each iteration has from 1 to 8 columns, and from 1 to 8 rows, and the frist N characters of the fxhash are displayed in one of first N positions (first 2 characters are discarted). If the number of characters is greater than 49 (length of fxhash discarting 'oo'), the boxes will continue to be filled, returning from the third character of fxhash.

Features generated by fxrand() random function:

-num_chars: number of characters displayed. from 1 to 64. They are the first N characters of fxhash.
-has_fxhash: this boolean value indicates whether fxhash contains the letters needed to form the word 'fxhash'.
-show_fxhash: this boolean value indicates whether fxhash contains the letters needed to form the word 'fxhash' and these are all displayed.
-columns: number of columns (1-8).
-rows: number of rows (1-8).
-color_mode: color mode white (light) or black (dark).
-separacio: factor of separation between barcodes (1.1, 1.5 or 2)
-scale_type: scale type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-rotate_type: rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-transparent: this boolean value indicates whether the barcodes has a transparent background.
-squares: this boolean value indicates whether the barcodes width=height.
-main_shadow: blur value for main shadow.
-exterior_shadow: exterior shadow type rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)
-interior_shadow: exterior shadow type rotation type (none, all, random, only rows, only columns, etc..)


(There are more values generated by fxrand() not shown as Feature)

click to show all fxhash barcodes, wich are displayed.

metadata.name: Action Painting #54
metadata.description:
In homage to Jackson Pollock. An algorithmic version of Action Painting.

My Fractions of the Whole algorithm organizes the space frame into areas for a tile comprised of closed paths of bezier line segments with random parameters. An underlying layer is tessellated with tiles made up of closed pathways are filled with a random color; that simulates the chance effects of dripping and spilling paint onto a canvas. Simulating the moving brush-in-hand, nine more iterations the image are overdrawn, each in separate random color, where the shapes are in outline (not filled). The result is a highly dynamic image that simulates the direct, instinctual, and spontaneous application of vigorous, sweeping lines of color.  

Check out Dr. Bill Generative Art OG website @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: CPoSOP Composition #23
metadata.description:
This is the second in series of works where we pay homage to Ken Knowlton, scientist and computer graphic pioneer and artist who passed on June 16, 2022. Ken Knowlton developed the famous EXPLOR language, (Explicit 2-D Patterns, Local Operations, and Randomness) while at Bell Labs. He published a paper describing it in 1975 entitled: MINI-EXPLOR, A FORTRAN-Coded Version of the EXPLOR Language for Mini (and larger) Computers. (https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/988049.988052)

This work is a mark of progress. Christopher Scussel and I are working on modernizing MINI-EXPLOR. Chris is working on updating the engine from the original FORTRAN code of the 1970’s and its other limitations to usable JavaScript. In concert, I am analyzing and synthesizing the capabilities of the code and identifying an aesthetic. Together we continue to update EXPLOR and add new features.

CPoSOP Composition is an original derivative work of Contour Plot of Superimposed Octagonal Pyramids that was one of Knowlton’s original test examples. (Example 3)

The original EXPLOR picture frame was limited to a fixed array of 140 x 140 “characters.” Chris has rewritten the code to make the picture space variable. In this piece I increased the image space to a resolution 250 x 250  picture cells. Each picture cell is a 3x3 pixel block. 

The EXPLOR functions are designed to interact with the current contents of each cell in the picture array. Every EXPLOR function has a rules parameter. In this test I’ve added a background. Thus when I draw my modified CPoSOP widget over the background it interacts with the color contents of a background cell or, the color of the cell based on a previously drawn widget.

I’ve modified the original CPoSOP code and replaced constants with random variables. (made it a Spatial Force). I create a regular grid (Form of Spatial Organization) of a random size and draw the CPoSOP widget 85% of the time in one of the grid elements positions. The grid provides a structure to the image and the CPoSOP widget provides visual interest. The interaction of the widgets with the background and each other are amazing. 

In keeping true to an EXPLOR vibe we use 4 color palettes. We let the computer randomly pick from three predefined palettes: Black and white. Four colors randomly chosen from set of 8 “Bauhaus” colors. And, four truly random colors.

We continue to honor the passing of Ken Knowlton with this NFT series. Here is an opportunity to collect an example image from the famous program he authored now updated by Scussel and Kolomyjec. A true piece of Computer Graphic Art history with a modern twist.

Dr. Bill Generative Art OG @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: Explora ex machina #2
metadata.description:
This is the fourth in series of works where we pay homage to Ken Knowlton, scientist and computer graphic pioneer and artist who passed on June 16, 2022. Ken Knowlton developed the famous EXPLOR language, (Explicit 2-D Patterns, Local Operations, and Randomness) while at Bell Labs. He published a paper describing it in 1975 entitled: MINI-EXPLOR, A FORTRAN-Coded Version of the EXPLOR Language for Mini (and larger) Computers. (https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/988049.988052)

Explora ex machina is about exploring EXPLOR. In many ways the EXPLOR language is a snapshot in time (1975) where its capabilities were limited by the technology of the era its was created.  Christopher Scussel and I are working on modernizing MINI-EXPLOR, he is working on the engine and I’m trying to put it through aesthetic trials. That’s exactly what this work is all about. The trick going forward will be to make it a usable creative tool without changing its character.

About this image. Back to the original EXPLOR picture plane size of 140x140,  5x5 pixel “cells” and 4 color palettes. The goal is to keep the EXPLOR retro vibe.

Explora ex machina is a set of some random number of three “primitives” chosen in no particular order. The members of the set consist of: A ribbon cable, a doughnut or “bit” (reminiscent of the original core memory of older machines), and single threads or wires. The things you would see if you opened up an old mainframe.

In EXPLOR drawing order is important. Each primitive has its own random variables which alter its appearance and its own rules for interacting with the background on to which it is placed. 

The ribbon cable is a group of cells drawn contiguously along a horizontal sinusoidal path. The cable width is a variable chunk of its defining block. With EXPLOR you can always see the block, placed here in the upper right corner of the picture plane. 

The bit consists of concentric rings drawn by a circle algorithm. The number of rings is fixed but their radii randomly scale. The colors of the rings cycle through the color palette.

Finally the vertical threads are single sinusoidal strands that visually tie the components of the composition together. The parameter of the threads’ curves and colors are random.

We continue to honor the passing of Ken Knowlton with this NFT series. Here is an opportunity to collect an example image from the famous program he authored now updated by Scussel and Kolomyjec. A true piece of Computer Graphic Art history with a modern twist.

(c)2022 Dr. Bill Kolomyjec and Christoper Scussel. All rights reserved.

metadata.name: Abstract Life #6
metadata.description:
The concept of organic, obtained from living systems, is said to be an effect that, like a plant and a living being, has grown in a completely dynamic manner in different degrees, and no factor except vital forces has prevented its growth. Organic creation is an example of this type. Léonard de Vinci believed in nature; he wrote, "Painting is a child of nature" in his opinion, art should be compatible with nature. His public image of creativity was "innovation while maintaining fidelity" to nature. According to Michelangelo, the form the artist gives to the materials is in the artist's mind and the materials themselves. Therefore, the artist is always in a metaphysical struggle with the form and secrets of nature. This is a revelatory process through which the artist discovers the mass of paper already hidden in his mind and the materials. As an architect, I tried to create this work while paying attention to the structuralism of shapes and forms in creation, inspired by the colors in nature and my experience in painting and illustration.

To spread the vibe of my beautiful community, minters will own 50% of royalty on each secondary sale.
Eighteen different color palettes and three different borders are used in this artwork.
Made in p5js
Created August 2022
Artist: @ChistaAi

metadata.name: Oxygen #98
metadata.description:
Oxygen makes strange forms of life thrive even in the darkest of places.

This is a generative piece using curated randomness to create textures, generate distortion fields, simulate growth and create compositions.

The work is best viewed in high resolution, but due to the time it takes to render, the preview image is capped to only 1000 pixels in height. You can change the resolution by pressing keys

- 'm' for medium  (height=2000px)
- 'l' for large (height=3500px)
- 'x' for extra large (height=5000px) 

outputs. 

Press 's' to save the output as a PNG file.

For even larger outputs, you can open the work in live mode and append the text '?size=10000' to the URL. Here, you can change the number (10000) to the desired height in pixels. 

Please note, that a very high-resolution image may take a very long time to render and some browsers are not able to save the image. However, even a 10000 pixels tall outputs have been generated during testing.
